{{Infobox military installation |name = Żonqor Battery |native_name = Batterija taż-Żonqor |location = [[Marsaskala]], [[Malta]] |image = Żonqor Battery 14.jpg |image_size=300px |caption = The battery and its ditch with advanced vegetation |type = [[Polygonal fort|Polygonal]] [[artillery battery]] |coordinates = {{coord|35|52|5.7|N|14|33|51.4|E|type:landmark|display=inline}} |ownership = |controlledby = |open_to_public = No |built = 1882–1886 |used = |builder = [[British Empire]] |materials = [[Limestone]] and [[Concrete]] |height = |condition = Neglected |battles = |events = }}
'''Żonqor Battery''' ({{lang-mt|Batterija taż-Żonqor}}) is an [[artillery battery]] in [[Marsaskala]], [[Malta]], standing on high ground overlooking Marsaskala Bay. It is a [[polygonal fort]] and was built by the [[British Empire|British]] from 1882 to 1886.
==History== Żonqor Battery was built by the British between 1882 and 1886 at a cost of £5000<ref>{{cite web|title=Marsaskala|url=http://www.douzelage.org/fileadmin/Documents/2009_Altea/ANNEX_K_Marsaskala.pdf|website=douzelage.org|accessdate=1 January 2015}} p. 7.</ref> (or £6000<ref>Guillaumier, Alfie (2005). ''Bliet u Rħula Maltin''. Volume 2. Klabb Kotba Maltin. p. 971. {{ISBN|99932-39-40-2}}, {{ISBN|99932-39-41-0}}.</ref>). It has a pentagonal shape, and it is surrounded by a 6 metre wide ditch. The firing positions and ammunition depots were located below ground level to protect them from enemy fire. Its gun crew and garrison were stationed at the nearby [[Fort Leonardo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Marsaskala|url=http://www.douzelage.org/fileadmin/Documents/2009_Altea/ANNEX_K_Marsaskala.pdf|website=douzelage.org|accessdate=1 January 2015}} p. 7.</ref>
[[File:Żonqor Battery 21.jpg|thumb|left|Żonqor Battery with rubble walls]] Soon after being completed, the battery was found out to be inadequate since the range of its [[RML 7 inch gun]]s did not reach the area of the bay they were supposed to defend. Due to this, new plans were made to defend the bay by Governor [[Lintorn Simmons]], but these were never implemented.
The battery is believed to have been armed with three canons,<ref>Guillaumier, Alfie (2005). ''Bliet u Rħula Maltin''. Volume 2. Klabb Kotba Maltin. p. 971. {{ISBN|99932-39-40-2}}, {{ISBN|99932-39-41-0}}.</ref> but it is said that they may have never been adjusted into place for use.<ref>Stephenson, Charles (2004). ''The Fortifications of Malta 1530-1945 (Fortress)''. Osprey Publishing. p. 6. {{ISBN|978-1841766935}}.</ref> The battery's guns were eventually dismantled, and in [[World War II]], the battery was used as a warehouse for ammunition.
==Present day== The battery is now used for agricultural purposes and it is not open to the public.<ref>{{cite web|title=Batterija Taz Zonqor|url=http://www.zonqor.com/marsaskala/batterija-taz-zonqor.html|website=zonqor.com|accessdate=1 January 2015|date=22 November 2010}}</ref>
